# Stack

- Python
- PyTorch for models
- NumPy / pandas / scikit-learn where appropriate
- Matplotlib or seaborn for standard figures unless otherwise specified

# Code organization

Prefer this structure:
- src/data/ for loading and preprocessing
- src/models/ for model definitions
- src/train/ for training loops
- src/eval/ for behavioral metrics
- src/neural/ for neural alignment analyses
- src/plot/ for figure code
- scripts/ for entry points

# Engineering rules

- Keep functions small and single-purpose.
- Avoid giant notebooks as the system of record.
- Put reusable logic in src/, not only in notebooks.
- Every major analysis should be reproducible from a script.
- Use config files or dataclasses for experiment settings.
- Do not bury assumptions in magic constants.
- Add docstrings to public functions.
- Save intermediate outputs with explicit names.

# Modeling rules

- Standardize the input/output contract across the three model classes.
- Keep evaluation code model-agnostic where possible.
- Separate training-time code from analysis-time code.
- Make latent extraction an explicit interface for each model.

# Analysis rules

- Behavior and neural analyses should each have standalone evaluation entry points.
- Switch-centered analyses should use clearly parameterized windows.
- Any behavior-matched neural comparison must explicitly document the matching criterion.
